Methods:
We split the cores and scanned the surface with a Geotek linescan camera, 
which digitally scans the surface of the sediment and generates a continuous red, 
green, and blue digital record of the sediment core surface.  A single composite 
record of color intensity was compiled by sampling the continuous downcore profiles 
of red, green, and blue color intensity from the core drives at an increment of 0.5 mm.  
The three color channels covary (r2 = 0.60-0.99) and we chose to use the red color 
channel to document the downcore concentration of the laminae in the record because 
it exhibits slightly higher variance than either the blue or green channels.

The age-model for the new record is based on the same radiocarbon chronology used by 
Rodbell et al.(1999). The laminae dated by AMS 14C of terrestrial microfossils in the 
Rodbell et al. (1999) record are distinctive and could be confidently identified in 
the new cores.  By creating a composite section from overlapping drives, we were able 
to improve on the original age model.  We adopted the constant carbon accumulation 
model (CCAM) and an event model (EM) to allocate time between dated intervals 
(Rodbell et al., 1999; Moy, 2000). The CCAM assumes that the rate of organic carbon 
deposition has remained nearly constant between radiocarbon-dated intervals through
the Holocene, and this continuous sedimentation was punctuated by nearly instantaneous 
clastic depositional events. The EM is based on the assumption that each of the clastic 
laminae was deposited during a single ENSO event with a temporal duration of 6 months, 
and we based this hypothesis on discharge data from the Rio Chira, which display high 
flow for a period of 6 months during an ENSO event (Martin et al., 1993).  
Clastic events were identified in the color intensity profile as peaks in color 
intensity units that exceed the surrounding background laminae by 15 color intensity 
units or more (Moy, 2000).  After time was assigned to the clastic laminae, the
remaining time was distributed linearly between radiocarbon dates.  One advantage 
of the EM over the CCAM is that it assigns equal magnitude to each of the events, 
thereby removing any effects that sediment compaction may have on the color of the 
light colored laminae at the base of the record.
